ar, the book identifies the modest successes and, sadly, the far more significant failures in government policy over the last decade. The authors also uncover why it has proved so difficult to adopt a more sustainable approach to transport and break Britain's love-affair with the car. The book reviews the links between the idea of sustainability and transport policy, and provides an up-to-the-minute analysis of the political realities surrounding the delivery of a sustainable transport agenda in the UK. It picks up on the principal components of A New Deal for Transport and evaluates to what extent these have, or haven't, been delivered in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. The contributors analyse why delivering sustainable transport policies seems to present particular difficulties to ministers across the UK, and considers the UK's experience in an international perspective. The book draws lessons from the last 10 years in order to better inform future policy development.  Traffic Jam is an indispensable analysis of the difficulties involved in turning policy ideals into practical reality, and as such will be of interest to scholars, students, planners, policy analysts and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aTransportation and statezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aAbrantes, Pedro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDocherty, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDocherty, Iain, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDudley, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel